
INSERT INTO public.knowledge_base (url, title, content, scraped_at)
VALUES
(
  'https://techfleet.medium.com/practices-the-invisible-components-that-drive-empowered-teamwork-5ee345fc10bd',
  'Practices: The Invisible Components That Drive Empowered Teamwork',
  E'# Practices: The Invisible Components That Drive Empowered Teamwork\n\n**Source:** [Tech Fleet Medium](https://techfleet.medium.com/practices-the-invisible-components-that-drive-empowered-teamwork-5ee345fc10bd)\n**Published:** August 14, 2025\n**Written by:** The pioneering Agile Coaching Community of Practice in Tech Fleet\n\n## Defining the Recipes for Successful Teamwork\n\nTech Fleet has built an open source taxonomy of team-based problem solving called the Skills and Practices Framework. With it, we''ve built a shared language around success. People can understand what it takes to succeed in empowered teamwork. It covers skills, tasks, duties, deliverables, workshops, methods, and many more components.\n\nWe''ve applied this taxonomy to our training experience for members. It lives among onboarding materials, user guides, agile coaching, and training templates. We use it to standardize how we approach team-based problem-solving, and how we speak to it.\n\n## Introducing Team Practices\n\nWe define two contributing factors of empowered teams:\n\n1. Empowered teams **build common values together.**\n2. Empowered teams **build common beliefs and behaviors** while working together to achieve outcomes.\n\nWe are reframing "soft skills and hard skills" to build future leaders. People-first leaders empower the people around them. They don''t just have skills; they hold different mindsets; they behave differently. We call these beliefs and behaviors "team practices".\n\n## How Teams Grow Together\n\nThe Four Stages of Team Development guide us:\n\n1. Forming Stage — teams get together and start getting to know each other.\n2. Storming Stage — teams get into conflict and start defining how they want to work together.\n3. Norming Stage — teams resolve healthy conflict and align in their work.\n4. Performing Stage — teams are empowered to innovate and perform the work in the ways they want.\n\n## Building Teams that Perform\n\nTeams must build shared values, shared beliefs, and shared behaviors to succeed in outcomes.\n\nFoundations of empowered teams:\n\n1. Values — Teammates align in shared values as a team.\n2. Beliefs — Teammates build common beliefs about teamwork from their own experiences and perspectives.\n3. Behaviors — Teammates act out their beliefs together through the work.\n4. Abilities — Teammates use their skills to perform activities together.\n\n## Human-Centered Abilities\n\nSkills are measured abilities that teammates have. Per the World Economic Forum''s 2025 Future of Jobs Report, the skills of the future are human-centered:\n\n1. Leadership\n2. Analytical thinking\n3. Resilience\n4. Adaptability\n5. Empathy\n6. Self-awareness\n\n## Human-Centered Beliefs and Behaviors\n\nPractices are shared beliefs and behaviors that teammates hold. Skills and experience aren''t enough to succeed. Teams require both skills and practices to succeed.\n\nPractices are more challenging than skills because they involve:\n\n1. Interactions with others\n2. Reflection\n3. Feedback\n4. Mindset shifts\n5. Intentional behavior changes\n6. Trial and error\n\n## Types of Practices\n\nWe''ve defined seven practices that affect empowered team success:\n\n1. **Empowerment** — The practice of building power in others. When people believe in empowerment, they believe everyone on the team brings value.\n2. **Service Leadership** — The practice of supporting others'' growth. They practice by building empathy and checking assumptions before acting.\n3. **Psychological Safety** — The practice of fostering belonging, learning, failure, and challenge. They provide space for multiple perspectives and encourage experimentation.\n4. **Continuous Improvement** — The practice of incremental growth. They experiment with new ways of work and adjust after failure.\n5. **Decision Making** — The practice of building consensus with others. They build consensus and ask for feedback before deciding.\n6. **Ownership** — The practice of taking and transferring ownership. They allow others to take over and finish what they commit to.\n7. **Agility** — The practice of adaptation and nimbleness. They show work in progress and change direction when warranted.\n\n## How To Measure Skills and Practices\n\nThe measurement cycle is continuous:\n\n1. Measure current levels of beliefs and behavior.\n2. Make a plan of action to work on something.\n3. Practice with teammates.\n4. Reflect on the practice with yourself and others.\n5. Define how to adjust.\n6. Take new measurements and repeat the cycle.\n\nTypes of assessments:\n\n1. Measuring team values\n2. Measuring confidence\n3. Self-reflections of feedback\n4. Peer reflections of feedback\n5. Tracking team outcomes',
  now()
),
(
  'https://techfleet.medium.com/a-comprehensive-tech-skills-information-architecture-for-new-grads-and-career-changers-57a9b747582d',
  'A Comprehensive Tech Skills Information Architecture for New Grads and Career Changers',
  E'# A Comprehensive Tech Skills Information Architecture for New Grads and Career Changers\n\n**Source:** [Tech Fleet Medium](https://techfleet.medium.com/a-comprehensive-tech-skills-information-architecture-for-new-grads-and-career-changers-57a9b747582d)\n**Published:** May 7, 2025\n**Written by:** Morgan Denner, Executive Director for Tech Fleet\n\nIt''s been five years since Tech Fleet''s mission started in 2020. Tech still has a lot of barriers today. Companies want experience and key industry skills that school can''t teach. The industry evolves at a faster pace than training programs.\n\nThis article introduces the next evolution to career training: a Tech Skills Information Architecture framework for the world to utilize. The framework is a first-of-its-kind information layer for tech training infrastructure.\n\n## Vision\n\nThis information layer offers a common language in technology career success. With it, trainees can understand how far they have come and how much they''ll have to train for a career they love. The framework can provide a foundation to measure readiness, progress, and success.\n\n## The Problems This Solves\n\n1. Different people have different opinions about necessary tech career skills to hold.\n2. Startup, agency, and in-house company skill expectations vary based on what they define.\n3. Different company job titles have different daily expectations.\n4. Buzzwords and jargon create misunderstandings about what skills and deliverables to practice.\n5. Schools and training programs teach basic hard skills. Companies expect team-focused soft skills.\n6. Skills, tasks, tools, deliverables, and experience relate to each other in complicated ways.\n\n## Key Value for Trainees\n\n1. It concretely explains skills, activities, deliverables, methods, and specializations involved in tech-related jobs.\n2. It breaks down the differences between skills for startups, agencies, and in-house companies.\n3. It helps trainees communicate skills as they build experience.\n4. It helps trainees tell the story about skills gained in previous work experience.\n5. It helps trainees make informed decisions about professional development gaps.\n\n## Key Value for Teams\n\n1. It helps teams standardize Agile Product Operations.\n2. It helps teams plan proper work outcomes.\n3. It helps employers make informed decisions about candidate skills.\n4. It provides a system to measure job readiness, progress, and success.\n\n## Key Value for Coaches and Teachers\n\n1. It explains key concepts through a shared language.\n2. It provides components of education curriculum that''s industry-focused.\n3. It can help educators build lessons around cross-functional team collaboration.\n\n## Background\n\nAn information architecture (in this case, an Ontology) portrays objects and their relationship to each other. This information architecture focuses on the subject of "Agile product and service development".\n\nThe 12 objects described in the framework:\n\n1. Company types\n2. Hard skills\n3. Soft skills\n4. Work tasks\n5. Tools\n6. Deliverables\n7. Methodologies\n8. Workshops\n9. Product milestones\n10. Specializations\n11. Commitments\n12. Job titles\n\n## A Shared Language of Tech Skills and Experience\n\nWith the framework''s shared language, we can discuss how there are "many roles per job title". We can speak to the variance people see in job expectations. We can build proper expectations about the work people agree to when they train on teams.\n\n## Agile Team Building for Beginners\n\nAgile has unique challenges for those who are new. The Tech Skills Framework provides ways to build training that helps beginners speak the language of Agile and know how to properly operate.\n\n## Agile Product Development Clarity\n\nThe Tech Skills Framework provides a relationship between milestones, deliverables, and work tasks. This helps teams understand everything they should be doing, and when, towards launching MVP and MMP products.\n\n## Helping Trainees Explore Possibilities\n\nSince the hard skills and soft skills for key job functions are outlined, we can compare skills people may have gained from previous careers to the skills they need in a desired career.\n\n## Effective Agile Project Management\n\nThe framework''s foundations of Agile product development helps new teams build comprehensive project planning. They can outline goals, outcomes, and deliverables necessary for project work even before they begin.\n\n## Where We Go from Here\n\n1. We''re going to keep building cross-functional team workshop templates to help newcomers.\n2. We''re going to build systems based on this framework for trainees to measure skill levels and experience levels.\n3. We''re going to work with key players in the industry to scale this framework.',
  now()
),
(
  'https://techfleet.medium.com/introducing-the-tech-fleet-community-dao-offering-decentralized-tech-apprenticeships-and-a-95fb35ab7abf',
  'Introducing Tech Fleet: Offering Decentralized Tech Training and a Participatory Economics Engine for The World',
  E'# Introducing Tech Fleet: Offering Decentralized Tech Training and a Participatory Economics Engine for The World\n\n**Source:** [Tech Fleet Medium](https://techfleet.medium.com/introducing-the-tech-fleet-community-dao-offering-decentralized-tech-apprenticeships-and-a-95fb35ab7abf)\n**Published:** March 22, 2022 (Last edited Jan 7, 2024)\n\n## Introduction\n\nNot everyone has an equal chance of success in Tech careers today. Where you grew up, your access to premium education, who you and your family know, your work experience, all play roles in your success. Those who are favored get the experience they need to land lucrative jobs. Others end up working a second job for free, just to get the experience they need.\n\nThe "Experience Firewall" — "Sorry, you need a year on the job for this entry-level role." The world''s supply of experienced Tech talent is shrinking while demand for skilled resources grows.\n\nTech Fleet is a bridge to the real world. A community focused on leveling the playing field for those getting into Tech, and bettering the standards of Agile UX in the industry.\n\n## Our Purpose\n\n### Develop People\n\n1. To provide a network for UX, product, development, and other tech roles\n2. To help people build experience, learn skills, practice industry methods, and continue education\n3. To foster experiential learning\n4. To advance skills through all stages of tech careers\n5. To provide opportunities for people with 0 to 5 years of tech experience\n6. To serve the best interests of new graduates and career changers\n7. To serve the best interest of UX, product, or development roles\n8. To build knowledge of tech professions and industry skills\n9. To offer tangible resources for education and training\n\n### Build Products\n\n1. To build open source products for the public good\n2. To offer professional tech services for the public good\n\n### Deliver Talent\n\n1. To connect hiring managers with rising tech talent\n2. To partner with recruiters and businesses to hire Tech Fleet talent\n\n## Tech Fleet Overview\n\nTech Fleet is on a mission to create equal opportunity to anyone pursuing UX, Product Management, Development, and other Tech fields. We want to give anyone in the world the opportunity to learn by doing, closing the education gap as we go.\n\nIn June 2020 we created Tech Fleet to create an opportunity for anyone, no matter who they are, to gain real-world experience in UX and Product while practicing job skills. Well over 100 apprentices from Tech Fleet have found full-time roles in UX and Product after each took on an 8-week apprenticeship.\n\n### The Problems We''re Solving\n\n1. We''ve got a hiring problem all over the world.\n2. The wealth gap and Tech skills gap continue to grow all over the world.\n3. New workers in Tech are not given enough proper chances to succeed.\n4. We''ve got a UX and Product talent problem in new industries like blockchain/web3, AI, and VR.\n5. There''s an ever-growing gap between educational knowledge and job requirements as industries evolve.\n6. Juniors and people transitioning from other fields are struggling the hardest to break into Tech.\n\n### Our Offerings\n\n1. A decentralized model for Tech apprenticeships; anyone in the world should have a chance to get on-the-job experience.\n2. Industry certifications, courses, events, and other resources for advanced topics in UX, product, or development.\n3. Experience building opportunities for entry-level workers, junior workers, experts, mentors, and coaches.\n4. A community-driven talent network of rising tech professionals offering UX, Product, Development, and other tech services.\n\n## The Value of Tech Fleet\n\n1. Offering apprenticeships in UX, Product, and development with real stake, real experience, real income, and real results.\n2. Tech Fleet training and experience building can teach in-demand skills that jobs teach you.\n3. User-Centered Design, Business Development, UX Research, Product Strategy, Development, and Marketing services for nonprofits and open source projects.\n4. Professional experience opportunities for Tech Fleet apprentices and leads, and for regular freelancers of any level.\n\n## How Are We Different\n\n1. **vs. Freelance and volunteering platforms** — None focus on helping inexperienced workers like we do. None give financial stake in the companies.\n2. **vs. Bootcamps and educational institutions** — We are the "Bootcamp of Hard Knocks". We teach the fundamentals of the industry unlike education. We teach Agile UX, perform Design Sprints, and give contributors psychological safety to make decisions and fail fast.\n3. **vs. Agencies** — Agencies only specialize in the skills they''ve hired for. Tech Fleet is a decentralized network of talent.\n4. **vs. Other communities** — Our organization is embedded in a philanthropic mission focused on bettering communities in Tech by creating fair access to tech careers.',
  now()
),
(
  'https://techfleet.medium.com/how-might-we-make-tech-fleet-talent-more-marketable-43ff3723c3ed',
  'How Might We Make Tech Fleet Talent More Marketable?',
  E'# How Might We Make Tech Fleet Talent More Marketable?\n\n**Source:** [Tech Fleet Medium](https://techfleet.medium.com/how-might-we-make-tech-fleet-talent-more-marketable-43ff3723c3ed)\n**Published:** March 30, 2024\n\n## The Problem\n\nWhat makes "breaking into tech" so hard?\n\nTech roles can be some of the most convoluted for which to qualify. People need on-the-job experience and need cross-functional skills. They often learn, or re-learn, these skills by contributing on a real team.\n\nThis doesn''t help new graduates or career changers who can''t find jobs. Without the skills and experience, how does one master the skills and experience?\n\nThe answer: Tech Fleet.\n\n## The Vision\n\nTech Fleet will push industry standards around "what it takes" to succeed in tech roles. So far, we have focused on experience building. From here, we will help others assess and prove their skills before and after Tech Fleet.\n\nContributors should be able to understand how far they have come and how far they have to go. Skills should be defined for individuals, roles, and Tech Fleet project phases. Tech Fleet will use skills measurements to match talent to training and paid work.\n\n## Tech Industry Hard Skills\n\n"Hard" skills, the skills you need for a specific role, vary across tech roles. People need to understand how they''d perform day-to-day. Some positions are more cross-functional and need training in other roles.\n\nExamples of tech industry hard skills:\n\n- UI design\n- Design systems and components\n- Content writing\n- Research methods\n- Research analysis\n- Customer experience design\n- Backlog management\n- Prioritization and scope\n- Requirements gathering\n- Product-market fit analysis\n- Front-end development\n\n## Tech Industry Soft Skills\n\nEducation offers the foundation of "hard" skills, while "soft" skills require experience. "Soft" skills are somewhat consistent between tech roles. These are the things that affect success in the role but have nothing to do with the role.\n\nExamples of tech industry soft skills:\n\n- Agile\n- Time management\n- Facilitation\n- Stakeholder management\n- Persuasion and buy-in generation\n- Coaching\n- Interpersonal dynamics\n- Communication\n- Leadership\n\n## Measuring "Marketability"\n\nWhat makes a candidate more likely to get hired than the next? We seek to define this in clear terms across all tech roles Tech Fleet supports. This involves a mix of skills and experience, and depends on the role.\n\nSome career paths need cross-functional experience to master the required skills. Some career paths have many levels of "mastery". With this framework, Tech Fleet contributors can drive their own success.\n\n## Working with the Industry\n\nOther organizations have defined skill levels in different tech roles. Tech Fleet should not "re-invent the wheel". We must garner interest and collaboration with the industry to ensure it''s accurate. Tech Fleet''s framework will be available "open source" for anyone to use or improve.',
  now()
)
